               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1144" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1144" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1144" type="surname" value="DALLAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1144" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM DALLAM</persName>
                  </hi>. I am servant to Walter Mornington, brass-finisher and gas-fitter, Frederick-street, Hampstead-road. On Saturday afternoon, the 3rd of Aug., I saw two coppers safe inside the lobby of his shop, between four and five o'clock, and about twenty minutes past five the prisoner was brought to the shop, with one of them—I then missed it—this is it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1145" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1145" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1145" type="surname" value="SWEET"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1145" type="given" value="ANDREW"></interp>ANDREW SWEET</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an ironmonger, and live in St. James's-place, Hampstead-road. On that Saturday afternoon I saw the prisoner and two others pass my shop—I lost sight of them, and soon after saw the prisoner come out of the prosecutor's shop, with a copper—I followed him—he dropped the copper, and I called, "Stop thief"—a butcher caught him.</p>
               <p>
